post_cb({"12317695": {"ParentId": "12317661", "CommentCount": "5", "CreationDate": "2012-09-07T12:01:04.277", "OwnerUserId": "346804", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "12317695", "Score": "2", "Body": "<p>Try it yourself:</p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;\n\nunion Foo    // Declare union type\n{\n    char   ch;\n\n    int func(int a);     \n};   \n\nint main()\n{\n    std::cout &lt;&lt; sizeof(Foo);\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Output:</p>\n<pre><code>1\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-09-07T12:01:04.277"}, "12317661": {"CommentCount": "1", "ViewCount": "138", "CreationDate": "2012-09-07T11:58:49.193", "LastActivityDate": "2012-09-07T12:06:00.897", "Title": "c++ classes as unions", "AcceptedAnswerId": "12317694", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "12317661", "Score": "0", "Body": "<p>I have found out that unions are classes in c++.</p>\n<p>If you declare a class as a union:</p>\n<pre>\nunion Foo    // Declare union type\n{\n    char   ch;\n\n    int func(int a);\n\n};          \n\n</pre>\n<p>Will the size of the union be 4 or 1 (assuming char size of 1 and pointers size of 4 ) ?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><oop><memory><unions>", "OwnerUserId": "1565284", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "12317694": {"ParentId": "12317661", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "3", "CreationDate": "2012-09-07T12:00:59.910", "Score": "3", "LastEditorUserId": "673730", "LastEditDate": "2012-09-07T12:06:00.897", "Id": "12317694", "OwnerUserId": "673730", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_12317661_12317694_0\">I have found out that unions are classes <strong>too</strong> in c++. (emphasis mine)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><del>No (they are a class-type, not classes).</del>My bad, apparently they are classes:</p>\n<h3>3.9.2/1</h3>\n<blockquote id=\"so_12317661_12317694_1\">\n<ul>\n<li>[...]</li>\n<li>unions, which are classes capable of containing objects of different types at different times</li>\n<li>[...]</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>(no longer relevant) Unions can't have <code>virtual</code> member functions &amp; also can't be used in inheritance.</p>\n<p><em>Onto the answer:</em></p>\n<p>The size will be large enough to accommodate the largest data member. In this case, it will likely be <code>1</code>, yes.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-09-07T12:06:00.897"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_12317661_12317694_1": {"section_id": 7221, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}}, "n3337": {"so_12317661_12317694_1": {"section_id": 6965, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}}, "n4659": {"so_12317661_12317694_1": {"section_id": 8730, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}}}});